---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import BrandBranchesGrid from '../../components/BrandBranchesGrid.astro';
import { MAIN_PHONE, MAIN_PHONE_TEL } from '../../data/branches';

const title = "Kold-Draft Ice Machine Repair | Southern California | Craft Cocktail";
const description = "Kold-Draft GT/KP-series 1 1/4\" perfect cube ice machine repair across Southern California. Craft cocktail specialists, Ali Group parts. $120. (424) 325-0520.";
const canonical = "https://samedayappliance.repair/brands/kold-draft-ice-machine-repair/";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Why do craft cocktail bars use Kold-Draft specifically?",
    a: "Three reasons, and they all connect to drink engineering. First, the 1-1/4-inch cube is dense and slow-melting — meaning dilution into a cocktail follows a predictable curve that bartenders can calibrate against, rather than the fast, aggressive dilution from smaller standard cubes. Second, the cubes are visually distinctive — clear, crystalline, photographable, which matters for premium cocktail presentation on Instagram-era bar programs. Third, the cube-formation process produces ice with fewer trapped impurities than standard cube machines, which means less off-flavor carryover into spirits. For a cocktail program where the ice itself is part of the menu, Kold-Draft is the category standard."
  },
  {
    q: "Is Kold-Draft part of Ali Group or still independent?",
    a: "Ali Group since 2021 (Kold-Draft International). Prior to the acquisition, Kold-Draft was an independent Michigan-based niche manufacturer; post-2021 it's part of the Ali Group ice family alongside Manitowoc (2022), Scotsman (2012), and Ice-O-Matic (2012). For service purposes, parts distribution has integrated into the broader Ali Group West Coast network, which improved LA parts availability substantially after the acquisition. Pre-2021 Kold-Draft machines occasionally see specific legacy parts that require longer lead times; post-acquisition machines flow through standard Ali Group channels."
  },
  {
    q: "What's the difference between Kold-Draft GT and KP series?",
    a: "GT is the flagship self-contained series — GT560, GT565, GT564, GT264 — with head-on-bin or integrated-bin configurations producing the 1-1/4-inch signature cube. Production ranges from about 380 to 630 lbs/day. KP is the modular production platform — higher capacity, head-on-bin, designed for central-production or high-volume bar programs that need to feed multiple service points. KP-series units run 900–1,400 lbs/day typical. GT is what most LA cocktail bars run; KP shows up at luxury hotels and multi-bar hospitality venues."
  },
  {
    q: "How often should a Kold-Draft unit be descaled?",
    a: "Quarterly in standard LA volume; every 6–8 weeks in high-volume cocktail bar operation. LA hard water is especially hard on Kold-Draft because the cube-formation process relies on very specific water-circuit behavior to achieve the crystalline clarity that defines the product. Scale buildup affects both freeze timing and cube appearance — cloudy cubes start showing before the unit runs into mechanical problems. A cocktail bar that serves 300+ drinks a Friday-Saturday needs preventive maintenance that an average restaurant operation doesn't."
  },
  {
    q: "Can you service Kold-Draft outside standard business hours?",
    a: "Yes. Kold-Draft failures almost always hit on peak service nights — because that's when the machines are pushed hardest. A Friday night bar failure on a Kold-Draft unit is a revenue emergency for a serious craft-cocktail program, so we run an after-hours emergency response protocol for Kold-Draft clients in the WeHo, DTLA, Santa Monica, and Arts District cocktail-bar clusters. That typically means Friday-Saturday night dispatch, Sunday same-day follow-up, and priority parts sourcing where needed."
  },
  {
    q: "What does Kold-Draft repair typically cost in LA?",
    a: "$120 commercial diagnostic, waived with repair. Kold-Draft parts run higher than generic cube-machine parts due to the specialty architecture and lower overall production volume. Typical calls: descaling $320–$460, water distribution manifold service $340–$540, water inlet valve $240–$380, ice thickness sensor $220–$340, harvest solenoid $340–$520, cube-plate evaporator service $480–$820, condenser cleaning + refrigerant $380–$620, GT-series control board $720–$1,350, compressor $1,000–$1,750 installed. Most tickets land $380–$900 parts and labor. After-hours emergency response adds a night-rate premium but is rarely a dealbreaker for serious cocktail programs where 48 hours of downtime costs significantly more."
  }
];

